      'art.obc.faq.q1':     'What does OBC Part 11 require for existing buildings?',
      'art.obc.faq.a1':     'Part 11 governs renovations and alterations. Key rules: alterations must not make the building less OBC-compliant than before; additions must meet current OBC; and change of use to a higher occupancy classification may trigger full structural upgrade of affected areas.',
      'art.obc.faq.q2':     'What is Ontario\'s balcony inspection requirement?',
      'art.obc.faq.a2':     'O.Reg 59/20 requires owners of residential buildings with 5+ storeys, 10+ units, built before 2001 to have balconies inspected by a P.Eng. or OAA architect every 5 years, with reports filed with the municipality. Non-compliance risks orders and civil liability.',
      'art.obc.faq.q3':     'What OHSA obligations apply to existing Ontario buildings?',
      'art.obc.faq.a3':     'OHSA Reg 851 requires ongoing structural integrity in industrial establishments. OHSA Reg 213/91 governs construction activity. Designated substance surveys are required before structural work disturbing building materials. MLITSD enforces all OHSA obligations.',
      'art.obc.faq.q4':     'What must an owner do if Toronto Building finds structural deficiencies?',
      'art.obc.faq.a4':     'Retain a P.Eng. immediately to assess the deficiency and prepare a remediation plan. File required building permit applications. Complete repairs within the timeline specified in the municipal order. Failure to comply enables the city to undertake repairs at the owner\'s expense plus penalties.',
      'art.obc.cta.h':      'OBC Compliance & Structural Inspections in Ontario',
      'art.obc.cta.p':      'Asvakas Engineering provides OBC compliance reviews, balcony inspections, and structural condition assessments for existing buildings across Ontario.',
      'art.obc.cta.btn':    'Request an OBC Compliance Review',
