      'art.fsi.h3.6':       'Construction Litigation & Arbitration',
      'art.fsi.faq.q1':     'What does a forensic structural engineer do in Ontario?',
      'art.fsi.faq.a1':     'Forensic structural engineers investigate the cause of structural distress, damage, or failure. They conduct site investigations, review documents, perform laboratory testing, and prepare written expert reports for use in insurance claims, litigation, arbitration, and remediation planning.',
      'art.fsi.faq.q2':     'When should I call a forensic structural engineer?',
      'art.fsi.faq.a2':     'Any time you observe unexpected cracking, sagging, settlement, or structural damage — particularly after a fire, flood, impact, adjacent excavation, or heavy loading event. Also for pre-purchase due diligence on commercial properties and when a structural failure requires investigation for insurance or legal purposes.',
      'art.fsi.faq.q3':     'Can a forensic report be used as expert evidence in Ontario court?',
      'art.fsi.faq.a3':     'Yes, if prepared in compliance with Rule 53.03 of the Ontario Rules of Civil Procedure. The report must include the expert\'s qualifications, the facts relied upon, the opinions, and a signed certificate that the expert\'s duty is to the court rather than to any party.',
      'art.fsi.faq.q4':     'How long does a forensic investigation take?',
      'art.fsi.faq.a4':     'A site visit takes one to two days. A written report is typically issued 3–6 weeks after the site visit for straightforward cases. Complex failures involving laboratory testing, finite element analysis, or multiple experts may take 8–16 weeks to reach final report.',
      'art.fsi.faq.q5':     'Is the forensic engineer\'s report confidential?',
      'art.fsi.faq.a5':     'Reports prepared for insurance or pre-litigation purposes may be protected by solicitor-client privilege or litigation privilege depending on when and how the engineer was retained. Once litigation is commenced and an expert report is disclosed under Rule 53.03, it becomes part of the court record and is no longer confidential.',
      'art.fsi.cta.h':      'Forensic Structural Investigation Across Ontario',
      'art.fsi.cta.p':      'Asvakas Engineering\'s P.Eng.-licensed professionals conduct forensic investigations, prepare Rule 53.03-compliant expert reports, and provide expert witness services for Ontario\'s property owners, insurers, and legal teams.',
      'art.fsi.sb.cta.h':   'Forensic Engineering Services',
      'art.fsi.sb.cta.p':   'Site investigations, expert reports, and P.Eng. testimony for Ontario insurance claims and construction litigation.',

