      'art.fag.h3.6':       'Inadequate Maintenance & Modification',
      'art.fag.faq.q1':     'What is structural failure analysis?',
      'art.fag.faq.a1':     'The systematic investigation of why a structural element or system failed — combining site inspection, material testing, and structural analysis to determine root cause. Findings are documented in a written expert report for insurance, litigation, or remediation use.',
      'art.fag.faq.q2':     'What are the most common causes of structural failure in Ontario?',
      'art.fag.faq.a2':     'Design deficiencies, construction deficiencies, material defects, overload, environmental deterioration (freeze-thaw, chloride corrosion), and inadequate maintenance or unauthorized modification. In practice, failures usually involve multiple contributing causes.',
      'art.fag.faq.q3':     'Does my insurer have the right to inspect before repairs?',
      'art.fag.faq.a3':     'Yes — most Ontario property insurance policies require that any damaged property be preserved for inspection by the insurer\'s adjuster and engineer before permanent repairs are made. Proceeding with repairs before the insurer has had an opportunity to inspect can jeopardize your claim. Emergency stabilization to prevent further damage is a standard exception.',
      'art.fag.faq.q4':     'How is an expert report different from an engineering assessment?',
      'art.fag.faq.a4':     'An engineering assessment reports observations and recommendations. An expert report additionally contains formal opinions on cause and responsibility, is prepared for use in legal proceedings, and includes a Rule 53.03 certificate. Not all engineering assessments are expert reports — the distinction matters for privilege, disclosure, and admissibility purposes in Ontario litigation.',
      'art.fag.faq.q5':     'What is the ODACC adjudication process for structural defects?',
      'art.fag.faq.a5':     'ODACC administers prompt payment and adjudication under the Ontario Construction Act. Adjudicators can decide disputes about construction defects, including structural deficiencies, within 30 days of appointment. Engineering expert reports in ODACC must be concise, accessible, and submitted within tight timelines.',
      'art.fag.cta.h':      'Structural Failure Analysis & Expert Reports in Ontario',
      'art.fag.cta.p':      'Asvakas Engineering prepares comprehensive failure analysis reports and Rule 53.03-compliant expert evidence for Ontario insurance claims, construction litigation, and ODACC adjudication.',
      'art.fag.sb.cta.h':   'Expert Engineering Reports',
      'art.fag.sb.cta.p':   'Failure analysis reports and Rule 53.03 expert evidence for Ontario courts, insurance claims, and arbitrations.',

